william higinbotham from wikipedia free encyclopedia jump navigation search william higinbotham born william higinbotham october bridgeport connecticut died november aged gainesville georgia cause death emphysema residence united states known for non-proliferation tennis for two william willy higinbotham october – november was american physicist member team that developed first nuclear bomb he later became leader nonproliferation movement he also has place history video games for his creation tennis for two first interactive analog computer game one first electronic games use graphical display contents early life career legacy references external links early life higinbotham was born bridgeport connecticut grew up caledonia new york his father was minister presbyterian church he earned his undergraduate degree from williams college continued his studies at cornell university he worked on radar system at mit from career exhibit tennis for two during world war ii he worked at los alamos national laboratory headed lab's electronics group later years war where his team developed electronics for first nuclear bomb his team created bomb's ignition mechanism well measuring instruments for device higinbotham also created radar display for experimental b-28 bomber following his experience with nuclear weapons higinbotham helped found nuclear nonproliferation group federation american scientists serving its first chairman executive secretary from until his death higinbotham served technical editor journal nuclear materials management published by institute nuclear materials management higinbotham took position at brookhaven national laboratory where he worked until his retirement head instrumentation division at brookhaven he created computer game called tennis for two for laboratory's annual exposition tennis simulator displayed on oscilloscope game credited with being one first video games game took higinbotham few weeks complete was popular attraction at show was such hit that higinbotham created expanded version for exposition this version allowed gravity level be changed so players could simulate tennis on jupiter moon higinbotham never patented tennis for two though he obtained over other patents during his career he recalled instruction book that came with computer described how plot trajectories bouncing shapes for research i thought hell this would make good game took me four hours design one technician couple weeks put together everybody stood line play other exhibits were pretty static obviously game seemed me sort obvious thing even if i had game would've belonged government legacy largely forgotten for years critics began recognize tennis for two's significance history video games 1980s david ahl who had played game at brookhaven exhibition teenager wrote cover story for creative computing which he dubbed higinbotham grandfather video games independently frank lovece interviewed higinbotham for story on history video games june issue video review stony brook university founded william higinbotham game studies collection managed by head special collections university archives kristen nyitray associate professor digital cultural studies raiford guins collection explicitly dedicated documenting material culture screen-based game media specific relation higinbotham collecting preserving texts ephemera artifacts that document history work early game innovator brookhaven national laboratory scientist william higinbotham who invented first interactive analog computer game tennis for two part preserving history tennis for two collection producing documentary on history game its reconstruction by peter takacs physicist at brookhaven national laboratory higinbotham remained little interested video games preferring be remembered for his work nuclear nonproliferation after his death requests for information on tennis for two increased his son william b higinbotham told brookhaven imperative that you include information on his nuclear nonproliferation work that was what he wanted be remembered for for this work federation american scientists named their headquarters higinbotham hall references b c d e f ronald sullivan november william higinbotham helped build first atomic bomb new york times retrieved may first video game bnlgov retrieved video games - did they begin at brookhaven ostigov january retrieved may b huhtamo erkki dismantling fairy engine media archaeology topos study huhtamo erkki parikka jussi media archaeology approaches applications implications university california press isbn retrieved may federation american scientists fas history fasorg retrieved journal nuclear materials management history archived from original on october retrieved wolf mark j p 'first' video game wolf mark j p encyclopedia video games abc-clio p isbn 031337936x retrieved may identified by brookhaven bob dvorak by first video game brookhaven national laboratory]] nd retrieved november b lovece frank june honest-to-goodness history home video games video review p retrieved september chaplin heather ruby aaron smartbomb quest for art entertainment big bucks videogame revolution algonquin books pp 35–36 isbn 1-56512-346-8 retrieved february william higinbotham game studies collection at stony brook university retrieved mission & goals william higinbotham game studies collection retrieved news william higinbotham game studies collection june retrieved chaplin heather ruby aaron smartbomb quest for art entertainment big bucks videogame revolution algonquin books p isbn 1-56512-346-8 retrieved february external links dot eaters entry on higinbotham his pong precursor who really invented video game editorial by john anderson from creative computing video & arcade games vol no / spring institute nuclear materials management inventorwilliam higinbotham biography william higinbotham game studies collection at stony brook university authority control worldcat identities viaf lccn n82220685 gnd retrieved from https//enw